<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1294,618,640]" box="[151,1294,618,640]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<taxonomicName authority="Huber, 2015: 7" authorityName=": Huber" authorityPageNumber="7" authorityYear="2015" box="[151,522,618,640]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Mesabolivar" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caipora">
<emphasis box="[151,364,618,640]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Mesabolivar caipora</emphasis>
Huber, 2015: 7
</taxonomicName>
–8, figs 10, 52–54 (♂ only; ♀ misidentified, see Note below; Brazil: Bahia).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1437,685,1718]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,214,685,710]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Note.</emphasis>
In the original description of this species, females were explicitly assigned with hesitation, and newly collected larger samples of males and females (see below) show that this assignment was wrong. The identity of the females assigned to 
<taxonomicName authority="in Huber (2015)" authorityName="in Huber" authorityYear="2015" box="[377,689,757,782]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Mesabolivar" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caipora">
<emphasis box="[377,501,758,781]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">M. caipora</emphasis>
in Huber (2015)
</taxonomicName>
remains unclear (see Note under description of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huber" authorityYear="2018" box="[1227,1353,757,782]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Mesabolivar" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="baianus">
<emphasis box="[1227,1353,757,782]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">M. baianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1437,685,1718]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,793,818]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
(amendments; see Huber 2015). Males are easily distinguished from known congeners by unique cheliceral armature (Huber 2015: fig. 54; distinctive oblique processes similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Keyserling" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[1069,1191,830,853]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Mesabolivar" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="togatus">
<emphasis box="[1069,1191,830,853]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">M. togatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but without proximal modification). Male palps appear indistinguishable from those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huber" authorityYear="2018" box="[886,1054,865,890]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Mesabolivar" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buraquinho">
<emphasis box="[886,1054,865,890]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">M. buraquinho</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Females differ from most known congeners by round sclerotized depression on anterior epigynal plate (
<figureCitation box="[1006,1104,901,926]" captionStart="FIGURES 184–187" captionStartId="49.[151,264,1170,1192]" captionTargetBox="[184,1412,194,1133]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[151,1436,193,1149]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURES 184–187. Mesabolivar buraquinho sp. n. (184–185, ZFMK Ar 19042) and M. caipora Huber, 2015 (186: ZFMK Ar 19062; 187: ZFMK Ar 19060). Epigyna, ventral views, and cleared female genitalia, dorsal views.Scale lines:0.3." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202565/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Fig 186</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1124,1226,902,926]" captionStart="FIGURES188–199" captionStartId="50.[151,264,1756,1778]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1735]" captionTargetId="figure@50.[151,1436,193,1735]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="FIGURES188–199. Femaleepigyna in ventral views and cleared female genitalia in dorsal views, Mesabolivar togatus group (part 1). 188–190.M.togatus (Keyserling, 1891), from Guapiaçú (188–189, ZFMK Ar 19017) and Sooretama (190, ZFMK Ar 19029).191–193.M.baianus sp. n., from Una (191–192, ZFMK Ar 19031) and Serra Bonita (193, ZFMK Ar 19038). 194.M. similis sp. n. (ZFMK Ar 19039). 195–196. M. camacan sp. n. (ZFMK Ar 19040). 197. M. buraquinho sp. n. (ZFMK Ar 19042).198–199.M.caiporaHuber, 2015, from São João (198, ZFMK Ar19062) and Mata do Crasto (199, ZFMK Ar 19060)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202567/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">198–199</figureCitation>
); they are barely distinguishable from females of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huber" authorityYear="2018" box="[541,717,937,962]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Mesabolivar" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buraquinho">
<emphasis box="[541,717,937,962]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">M. buraquinho</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(compare 
<figureCitation box="[851,1068,937,962]" captionStart="FIGURES 184–187" captionStartId="49.[151,264,1170,1192]" captionTargetBox="[184,1412,194,1133]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[151,1436,193,1149]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURES 184–187. Mesabolivar buraquinho sp. n. (184–185, ZFMK Ar 19042) and M. caipora Huber, 2015 (186: ZFMK Ar 19062; 187: ZFMK Ar 19060). Epigyna, ventral views, and cleared female genitalia, dorsal views.Scale lines:0.3." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202565/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Figs 184 and 186</figureCitation>
; median depression apparently consistently slightly larger in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="in Huber" authorityYear="2015" box="[483,607,974,997]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Mesabolivar" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caipora">
<emphasis box="[483,607,974,997]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">M. caipora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
